<table>
<thead><tr><th colspan="2" bgcolor="#2C6BFF" border="3" style="text-align: center; color: white; font-size: large;" width="50%"><b>Unix</b></th><th bgcolor="#2C6BFF" border="3" style="text-align: center; color: white; font-size: large;"><b>Linux</b></th></tr></thead>
<tbody><tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#FBE0C9" style="color: black;"><ul><li><p style="color: black;">Unix was first developed for multi-user and multi-tasking in mid-1970 in Bell Labs by AT&amp;T, General Electric (GE) and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).</p></li><li><p style="color: black;">Unix derivatives are mostly used by MacOS, iOS, Solaris, AIX, HP-UX, and more.</p></li><li><p style="color: black;">Unix can not be installed on any hardware because it only supports very fewer File systems.</p></li></ul></td>
<td bgcolor="#FBE0C9"><ul><li><p style="color: black;">Linux was developed in 1991 by Linus Torvalds.</p></li><li><p style="color: black;">Linux is open-source except few Enterprise Editions.</p></li><li><p style="color: black;">Linux is used by many developers, communities, or companies (Redhat, CentOS, AIX, and more.</p></li><li><p style="color: black;">Linux can be installed on a wide variety of computer hardware such as mobile phones, video game consoles, supercomputers, tablets, etc.</p></li></ul></td></tr>
     </tbody> </table>
